Command and entry point (difference between cmd and entry point in docker files)

Dockerfiles for a few commonly used Docker Images are given in the /root (current) directory. Inspect them and try to answer the questions in the subsequent tasks.
1.What is the ENTRYPOINT configured on the mysql image Dockerfile?

root@docker-host ~ ➜  cat Dockerfile-mysql | grep ENTRYPOINT
# Optional custom entrypoint (comment together with ENTRYPOINT below once you decide to build)
ENTRYPOINT ["docker-entrypoint.sh"]

2.What is the CMD configured on the wordpress image?

root@docker-host ~ ➜  cat Dockerfile-wordpress | grep CMD
CMD ["apache2-foreground"]

3.What is the final command run at startup when the wordpress image is run?
Consider both ENTRYPOINT and CMD instructions.

root@docker-host ~ ➜  cat Dockerfile-wordpress | grep CMD
CMD ["apache2-foreground"]

root@docker-host ~ ➜  cat Dockerfile-wordpress | grep ENTRYPOINT
ENTRYPOINT ["docker-entrypoint.sh"]

4.Which command runs at startup when the ubuntu image starts?
root@docker-host ~ ➜  cat Dockerfile-ubuntu | grep CMD
CMD ["bash"]

5.Run an instance of the ubuntu image that executes the sleep 1000 command at startup.

Note: Run it in detached mode.
root@docker-host ~ ➜  docker run -d  ubuntu sleep 1000
0050d9474acc771efbf2054f4790d24ae5e9ad58cc2a6565363b6b6d891dce59
